-- #412 CONTROL — DICT-SEMANTICS §6.1.3 (rigid commit) must survive the #412 fix.
--
-- The #412 fix makes `assum` reachable for a STRUCTURED given (`requires S (List a)`), so
-- an impl body forwards the construction site's most-specific dict instead of statically
-- committing to the general instance. This fixture pins the boundary of that: with a
-- BARE-TYVAR given (`requires S a`), the given `S a` does NOT match the body's goal
-- `S (List a)` — matching is structural on rigid variables, never unification — so `assum`
-- correctly stays silent, `inst` fires on a rigid goal, and the goal matches only the
-- GENERAL `impl S (List a)`, even though `impl S (List Int)` exists and the call is at
-- `List Int`. §6.1.3: selection commits at the elaboration site; it is not retroactively
-- re-resolved when `a := Int`.
--
-- ⚠️ The expected value here is 2, NOT 3. A reading of the fix that makes this print 3 is
-- WRONG — it would mean the given was matched by unification.
--
-- BUILD-ONLY on purpose: `medaka run` on this exact shape crashes
-- (`E-NOT-A-FUNCTION: applied non-function: 2`) — a separate, PRE-EXISTING bug, measured
-- unchanged on a pre-#412 binary, so the #412 fix neither caused nor cures it. This cell
-- is pinned where it is measurable rather than not pinned at all.
--
-- Two things about that crash are MEASURED (both on this fixture, this tree): it needs the
-- overlapping `impl S (List Int)` to be in scope — delete that impl and `run` prints 2
-- again — and its symptom is character-for-character the one
-- test/eval_dict_fixtures/impl_requires_terminal_body.mdk's header describes for #413 ("the
-- dict lands in the first value param and the real argument is then applied to the RESULT
-- — applied non-function: 2"). Whether it IS that gate re-opening under overlap is a
-- HYPOTHESIS, not something this fixture establishes — do not cite it as a root cause.
interface S a where
  s : a -> Int

interface P a where
  p : a -> Int

impl S Int where
  s _ = 1

impl S (List a) requires S a where
  s _ = 2

impl S (List Int) where
  s _ = 3

-- BARE-TYVAR given: `S a`, not `S (List a)`
impl P (List a) requires S a where
  p x = s x

main : <IO> Unit
main =
  -- p [1,2] → impl P (List a) at a:=Int. Body goal is S (List a) over RIGID a; the given
  -- in scope is S a, which is not that goal ⇒ assum silent ⇒ inst at the rigid goal ⇒
  -- only impl S (List a) matches ⇒ 2. NOT 3.
  println (p [1, 2])
